# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jet-fuel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] From the mid-1980s to September 2003, the inflation-adjusted price of a barrel of crude oil on NYMEX was generally under US$25/barrel in 2008 dollars.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Commentators attributed these price increases to multiple factors, including Middle East tension, soaring demand from China, the falling value of the U.S. dollar, reports showing a decline in petroleum reserves, worries over peak oil, and financial speculation.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] For a time, geopolitical events and natural disasters had strong short-term effects on oil prices, such as North Korean missile tests, the 2006 conflict between Israel and Lebanon, worries over Iranian nuclear plans in 2006, Hurricane Katrina, and various other factors.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] By 2008, such pressures appeared to have an insignificant impact on oil prices given the onset of the global recession.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The recession caused demand for energy to shrink in late 2008, with oil prices collapsing from the July 2008 high of $147 to a December 2008 low of $32.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] However, it has been disputed that the laws of supply and demand of oil could have been responsible for an almost 80% drop in the oil price within a six-month period.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Oil prices stabilized by August 2009 and generally remained in a broad trading range between $70 and $120 through November 2014, before returning to 2003 pre-crisis levels by early 2016, as US production increased dramatically.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The United States went on to become the largest oil producer by 2018.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The price of crude oil in 2003 traded in a range between $20–$30/bbl.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Between 2003 and July 2008, prices steadily rose, reaching $100/bbl in late 2007, coming close to the previous inflation-adjusted peak set in 1980.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] A steep rise in the price of oil in 2008 – also mirrored by other commodities – culminated in an all-time high of $147.27 during trading on 11 July 2008, more than a third above the previous inflation-adjusted high.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] High oil prices and economic weakness contributed to a demand contraction in 2007–2008.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In the United States, gasoline consumption declined by 0.4% in 2007, then fell by 0.5% in the first two months of 2008 alone.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Detailed analysis of changes in oil price from 1970–2007.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] World crude oil demand grew an average of 1.76% per year from 1994 to 2006, with a high of 3.4% in 2003–2004.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] World demand for oil is projected to increase 37% over 2006 levels by 2030, according to the 2007 U.S.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Energy Information Administration's (EIA) annual report.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2007, the EIA expected demand to reach an ultimate high of 118 million barrels per day (18.8×10^6 m3/d), from 2006's 86 million barrels (13.7×10^6 m3), driven in large part by the transportation sector.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] A 2008 report from the International Energy Agency (IEA) predicted that although drops in petroleum demand due to high prices have been observed in developed countries and are expected to continue, a 3.7 percent rise in demand by 2013 is predicted in developing countries.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This is projected to cause a net rise in global petroleum demand during that period.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Transportation consumes the largest proportion of energy, and has seen the largest growth in demand in recent decades.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This growth has largely come from new demand for cars and other personal-use vehicles powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This sector also has the highest consumption rates, accounting for approximately 55% of oil use worldwide as documented in the Hirsch report and 68.9% of the oil used in the United States in 2006.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Cars and trucks are predicted to cause almost 75% of the increase in oil consumption by India and China between 2001 and 2025.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2008, auto sales in China were expected to grow by as much as 15–20 percent, resulting in part from economic growth rates of over 10 percent for five years in a row.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Demand growth is highest in the developing world, but the United States is the world's largest consumer of petroleum.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] China, by comparison, increased consumption from 3.4 million barrels (540,000 m3) a day to 7 million barrels (1,100,000 m3) a day, an increase of 3.6 million barrels (570,000 m3) a day, in the same time frame.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Per capita, annual consumption is 24.85 barrels (3.951 m3) by people in the US, 1.79 barrels (0.285 m3) in China, and 0.79 barrels (0.126 m3) in India.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] As countries develop, industry, rapid urbanization and higher living standards drive up energy use, most often of oil.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Thriving economies such as China and India are quickly becoming large oil consumers.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] China has seen oil consumption grow by 8% yearly since 2002, doubling from 1996–2006.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Although swift continued growth in China is often predicted, others predict that China's export-dominated economy will not continue such growth trends due to wage and price inflation and reduced demand from the US.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] India's oil imports are expected to more than triple from 2005 levels by 2020, rising to 5 million barrels per day (790×10^3 m3/d).
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Another large factor on petroleum demand has been human population growth.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Because world population grew faster than oil production, production per capita peaked in 1979 (preceded by a plateau during the period of 1973–1979).
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The world’s population in 2030 is expected to be double that of 1980.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] State fuel subsidies shielded consumers in multiple nations from higher market prices, but a number of these subsidies were reduced or removed as the governmental cost rose.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] An important contributor to the price increase was the slowdown in oil supply growth, which has been a general trend since oil production surpassed new discoveries in 1980.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The likelihood that global oil production will decline at some point, leading to lower supply, is a long-term fundamental cause of rising prices.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Although there is contention about the exact time at which global production will peak, a majority of industry participants acknowledge that the concept of a production peak is valid.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] However, some commentators argued that global warming awareness and new energy sources would limit demand before the effects of supply could, suggesting that reserve depletion would be a non-issue.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] A large factor in the lower supply growth of petroleum has been that oil's historically high ratio of Energy Returned on Energy Invested is in significant decline.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Petroleum is a limited resource, and the remaining accessible reserves are consumed more rapidly each year.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Remaining reserves are increasingly difficult to extract and therefore more expensive.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Eventually, reserves will only be economically feasible to extract at extremely high prices.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Even if total oil supply does not decline, increasing numbers of experts believe the easily accessible sources of light sweet crude are almost exhausted and in the future the world will depend on more-expensive unconventional oil reserves and heavy crude oil, as well as renewable energy sources.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] It is thought by a number of people, including energy economists such as Matthew Simmons, that prices could continue to rise indefinitely until a new market equilibrium is reached at which point supply satisfies worldwide demand.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Timothy Kailing, in a 2008 *Journal of Energy Security* article, pointed out the difficulty of increasing production in mature petroleum regions, even with vastly increased investment in exploration and production.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] By looking at the historical response of production to variation in drilling effort, he claimed that very little increase of production could be attributed to increased drilling.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This was due to a tight quantitative relationship of diminishing returns with increasing drilling effort: As drilling effort increased, the energy obtained per active drill rig was reduced according to a severely diminishing power law.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This analysis suggested that even an enormous increase of drilling effort was unlikely to lead to significantly increased oil and gas production in a mature petroleum region like the United States.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] A prominent example of investment in non-conventional sources is seen in the Canadian oil sands.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] They are a far less cost-efficient source of heavy, low-grade oil than conventional crude; but when oil trades above $60/bbl, the tar sands become attractive to exploration and production companies.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] While Canada's oil sands region is estimated to contain as much "heavy" oil as all the world's reserves of "conventional" oil, efforts to economically exploit these resources lag behind the increasing demand of recent years.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Until 2008, CERA (a consulting company wholly owned by energy consultants IHS Energy) did not believe this would be such an immediate problem.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] However, in an interview with *The Wall Street Journal,* Daniel Yergin, previously known for his quotes that the price of oil would soon return down to "normal", amended the company's position on 7 May 2008 to predict that oil would reach $150 during 2008, due to tightness of supply.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This reversal of opinion was significant, as CERA, among other consultancies, provided price projections that were used by multiple official bodies to plan long-term strategy in respect of energy mix and price.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Other major energy organisations, such as the International Energy Agency (IEA), had already been much less optimistic in their assessments for some time.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2008, the IEA drastically accelerated its prediction of production decline for existing oilfields, from 3.7% a year to 6.7% a year, based largely on better accounting methods, including actual research of individual oil field production throughout the world.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Terrorist and insurgent groups have increasingly targeted oil and gas installations, and succeeded in stopping a substantial volume of exports during the 2003–2008 height of the American occupation of Iraq.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Such attacks are sometimes perpetrated by militias in regions where oil wealth has produced few tangible benefits for the local citizenry, as is the case in the Niger Delta.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] A number of factors have resulted in possible and/or actual concerns about the reduced supply of oil.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The post-9/11 war on terror, labor strikes, hurricane threats to oil platforms, fires and terrorist threats at refineries, and other short-lived problems are not solely responsible for the higher prices.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Such problems do push prices higher temporarily, but have not historically been fundamental to long-term price increases.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Investment demand for oil occurs when investors purchase *futures contracts* to buy a commodity at a set price for future delivery.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] "Speculators are not buying any actual crude. ...
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Several claims have been made implicating financial speculation as a major cause of the price increases.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In May 2008 the transport chief for Germany's Social Democrats estimated that 25 percent of the rise to $135 a barrel had nothing to do with underlying supply and demand.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Senate committee in May indicating that "demand shock" from "institutional investors" had increased by 848 million barrels (134,800,000 m3) over the previous five years, almost as much as the increased physical demand from China (920 million barrels (146,000,000 m3)).
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The influence of institutional investors, such as sovereign wealth funds, was also discussed in June 2008, when Lehman Brothers suggested that price increases were related to increases in exposure to commodities by such investors.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In June 2008, OPEC's Secretary General Abdallah Salem el-Badri stated that current world consumption of oil at 87 million bpd was far exceeded by the "paper market" for oil, which equaled about 1.36 billion bpd, or more than 15 times the actual market demand.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] An interagency task force on commodities markets was formed in the U.S. government to investigate the claims of speculators' influence on the petroleum market.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The task force concluded in July 2008 that "market fundamentals" such as supply and demand provided the best explanations for oil price increases, and that increased speculation was not statistically correlated with the increases.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The report also noted that increased prices with an elastic supply would cause increases in petroleum inventories.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] As inventories actually declined, the task force concluded that market pressures were most likely to blame.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Other commodities that were not subject to market speculation (such as coal, steel, and onions) saw similar price increases over the same time period.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In June 2008 U.S. energy secretary Samuel Bodman said that insufficient oil production, not financial speculation, was driving rising crude prices.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] He said that oil production had not kept pace with growing demand.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] "In the absence of any additional crude supply, for every 1% of crude demand, we will expect a 20% increase in price in order to balance the market," Bodman said.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This contradicted earlier statements by Iranian OPEC governor Mohammad-Ali Khatibi indicating that the oil market was saturated and that an increase in production announced by Saudi Arabia was "wrong".
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In September 2008, Masters Capital Management released a study of the oil market, concluding that speculation did significantly impact the price.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The study stated that over $60 billion was invested in oil during the first six months of 2008, helping drive the price per barrel from $95 to $147, and that by the beginning of September, $39 billion had been withdrawn by speculators, causing prices to fall.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] There is debate over what the **effects of the 2000s energy crisis** will be over the long term.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Some speculated that an oil-price spike could create a recession comparable to those that followed the 1973 and 1979 energy crises or a potentially worse situation such as a global oil crash.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Increased petroleum prices are reflected in a vast number of products derived from petroleum, as well as those transported using petroleum fuels.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In addition to high oil prices, from year 2000 volatility in the price of oil has increased notably and this volatility has been suggested to be a cause of the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The perceived increase in oil price differs internationally according to currency market fluctuations and the purchasing power of currencies.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] On average, oil prices roughly quadrupled for these areas, triggering widespread protest activities.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] A similar price surge for petroleum-based fertilizers contributed to the 2007–08 world food price crisis and further unrest.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2008, a report by Cambridge Energy Research Associates stated that 2007 had been the year of peak gasoline usage in the United States, and that record energy prices would cause an "enduring shift" in energy consumption practices.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] According to the report, in April gas consumption had been lower than a year before for the sixth straight month, suggesting 2008 would be the first year U.S. gasoline usage declined in 17 years.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The total miles driven in the U.S. began declining in 2006.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In the United States, oil prices contributed to inflation averaging 3.3% in 2005–2006, significantly above the average of 2.5% in the preceding 10-year period.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] As a result, during this period the Federal Reserve steadily raised interest rates to curb inflation.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] High oil prices typically affect less-affluent countries first, particularly the developing world with less discretionary income.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] There are fewer vehicles per capita, and oil is often used for electricity generation as well as private transport.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The World Bank has looked more deeply at the effect of oil prices in the developing countries.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] One analysis found that in South Africa a 125 percent increase in the price of crude oil and refined petroleum reduces employment and GDP by approximately 2 percent, and reduces household consumption by approximately 7 percent, affecting mainly the poor.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] OPEC's annual oil export revenue surged to a new record in 2008, estimated around US$800 billion.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] According to informed observers, OPEC, meeting in early December 2007, seemed to desire a high but stable price that would deliver substantial needed income to the oil-producing states, but avoid prices so high that they would negatively impact the economies of the oil-consuming nations.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] A range of US$70–80 per barrel was suggested by some analysts to be OPEC's goal.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In November 2008, as prices fell below $60 a barrel, the IEA warned that falling prices could lead to both a lack of investment in new sources of oil and a fall in production of more-expensive unconventional reserves such as the oil sands of Canada.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The IEA's chief economist warned, "Oil supplies in the future will come more and more from smaller and more-difficult fields," meaning that future production requires more investment every year.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] A lack of new investment in such projects, which had already been observed, could eventually cause new and more-severe supply issues than had been experienced in the early 2000s according to the IEA.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Because the sharpest production declines had been seen in developed countries, the IEA warned that the greatest growth in production was expected to come from smaller projects in OPEC states, raising their world production share from 44% in 2008 to a projected 51% in 2030.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The IEA also pointed out that demand from the developed world may have also peaked, so that future demand growth was likely to come from developing nations such as China, contributing 43%, and India and the Middle East, each about 20%.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] By the beginning of September 2008, prices had fallen to $110.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] OPEC Secretary General El-Badri said that the organization intended to cut output by about 500,000 barrels (79,000 m3) a day, which he saw as correcting a "huge oversupply" due to declining economies and a stronger U.S. dollar.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] On 10 September, the International Energy Agency (IEA) lowered its 2009 demand forecast by 140,000 barrels (22,000 m3) to 87.6 million barrels (13,930,000 m3) a day.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] As countries throughout the world entered an economic recession in the third quarter of 2008 and the global banking system came under severe strain, oil prices continued to slide.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In November and December, global demand growth fell, and U.S. oil demand fell an estimated 10% overall from early October to early November 2008 (accompanying a significant drop in auto sales).
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In their December meeting, OPEC members agreed to reduce their production by 2.2 million barrels (350,000 m3) per day, and said their resolution to reduce production in October had an 85% compliance rate.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Petroleum prices fell below $35 in February 2009, but by May 2009 had risen back to mid-November 2008 levels around $55.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The global economic downturn left oil-storage facilities with more oil than in any year since 1990, when Iraq's invasion of Kuwait upset the market.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In early 2011, crude oil rebounded above US$100/bbl due to the Arab Spring protests in the Middle East and North Africa, including the 2011 Egyptian revolution, the 2011 Libyan civil war, and steadily tightening international sanctions against Iran.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The oil price fluctuated around $100 through early 2014.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] By 2014–2015, the world oil market was again steadily oversupplied, led by an unexpected near-doubling in U.S. oil production from 2008 levels due to substantial improvements in shale "fracking" technology.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] By January 2016, the OPEC Reference Basket fell to US$22.48/bbl – less than one-sixth of its record from July 2008 ($140.73), and back below the April 2003 starting point ($23.27) of its historic run-up.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] OPEC production was poised to rise further with the lifting of Iranian sanctions, at a time when markets already appeared to be oversupplied by at least 2 million barrels per day.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In mainstream economic theory, a free market rations an increasingly scarce commodity by increasing its price.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] A higher price should stimulate producers to produce more, and consumers to consume less, while possibly shifting to substitutes.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The first three mitigation strategies in the above list are, therefore, in keeping with mainstream economic theory, as government policies can affect the supply and demand for petroleum as well as the availability of substitutes.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In contrast, the last type of strategy in the list (attempting to shield consumers from rising prices) would seem to work against classical economic theory, by encouraging consumers to overconsume the scarce quantity, thus making it even scarcer.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] To avoid creating outright shortages, attempts at price control may require some sort of rationing scheme.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Economists say that the substitution effect will spur demand for alternate fossil fuels, such as coal or liquefied natural gas and for renewable energy, such as solar power, wind power, and advanced biofuels.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] For example, China and India are currently heavily investing in natural gas and coal liquefaction facilities.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Nigeria is working on burning natural gas to produce electricity instead of simply flaring the gas, where all non-emergency gas flaring will be forbidden after 2008.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Outside the U.S., more than 50% of oil is consumed for stationary, non-transportation purposes such as electricity production where it is relatively easy to substitute natural gas for oil.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Oil companies including the supermajors have begun to fund research into alternative fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] BP has invested half a billion dollars for research over the next several years.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The motivations behind such moves are to acquire the patent rights as well as understanding the technology so vertical integration of the future industry could be achieved.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The rise in oil prices caused renewed interest in electric cars, with several new models hitting the market, both hybrid and purely electric.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The most successful among the former being the Toyota Prius and among the latter the cars of companies like Tesla.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Several countries also incentivized the use of electric cars through tax-breaks or subsidies or by building charging stations.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In a similar vein as the original TGV that was switched from gas turbine to electric propulsion after the 1973 oil crisis, several countries have renewed and increased their efforts for electric propulsion in their rail systems, specifically high-speed rail.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In the time since 2003, the global High speed rail network almost doubled and there are plans globally that amount to the network being doubled again within the next ten to twenty years, based on current constructions.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] China in particular went from having no high-speed rail whatsoever in 2003 to having the longest network in the world in 2015.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Another major factor in petroleum demand is the widespread use of petroleum products such as plastic.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] These could be partially replaced by bioplastics, which are derived from renewable plant feedstocks such as vegetable oil, cornstarch, pea starch, or microbiota.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] They are used either as a direct replacement for traditional plastics or as blends with traditional plastics.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The most common end use market is for packaging materials.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Japan has also been a pioneer in bioplastics, incorporating them into electronics and automobiles.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Bioasphalt can also be used as a replacement of petroleum asphalt.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The United States Strategic Petroleum Reserve could, on its own, supply current U.S. demand for about a month in the event of an emergency, unless it were also destroyed or inaccessible in the emergency.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This could potentially be the case if a major storm were to hit the Gulf of Mexico, where the reserve is located.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] While total consumption has increased, the western economies are less reliant on oil than they were twenty-five years ago, due both to substantial growth in productivity and the growth of sectors of the economy with little oil dependence such as finance and banking, retail, etc.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The decline of heavy industry and manufacturing in most developed countries has reduced the amount of oil per unit GDP; however, since these items are imported anyway, there is less change in the oil dependence of industrialized countries than the direct consumption statistics indicate.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] One recourse used and discussed in the past to avoid the negative impacts of oil shocks in the a number of developed countries which have high fuel taxes has been to temporarily or permanently suspend these taxes as fuel costs rise.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] France, Italy, and the Netherlands lowered taxes in 2000 in response to protests over high prices, but other European nations resisted this option because public service finance is partly based on energy taxes.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The issue came up again in 2004, when oil reached $40 a barrel causing a meeting of 25 EU finance ministers to lower economic growth forecasts for that year.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Because of budget deficits in several countries, they decided to pressure OPEC to lower prices instead of lowering taxes.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In 2007, European truckers, farmers, and fishermen again raised concerns over record oil prices cutting into their earnings, hoping to have taxes lowered.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] In the United Kingdom, where fuel taxes were raised in October and were scheduled to rise again in April 2008, there was talk of protests and roadblocks if the tax issue was not addressed.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] On 1 April 2008, a 25 yen per liter fuel tax in Japan was allowed to lapse temporarily.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This method of softening price shocks is even less viable to countries with much lower gas taxes, such as the United States.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Locally decreasing fuel tax can decrease fuel prices, but globally prices are set by supply and demand, and therefore fuel tax decreases may have no effect on fuel prices, and fuel tax increases might actually decrease fuel prices by reducing demand.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] But this depends on the price elasticity of demand for fuel which is -0.09 to -0.31, meaning that fuel is a relatively inelastic commodity, i.e. increasing or decreasing prices have overall only a small effect on demand and therefore price change.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Transportation demand management has the potential to be an effective policy response to fuel shortages or price increases and has a greater probability of long term benefits than other mitigation options.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] There are major differences in energy consumption for private transport between cities; an average U.S. urban dweller uses 24 times more energy annually for private transport as a Chinese urban resident.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] These differences cannot be explained by wealth alone but are closely linked to the rates of walking, cycling, and public transport use and to enduring features of the city including urban density and urban design.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] For individuals, remote work provides alternatives to daily commuting and long-distance air travel for business.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Technologies such as videoconferencing, e-mail, and corporate wikis, continue to improve.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] As the cost of moving human workers continues to rise, while the cost of moving information electronically continues to fall, presumably market forces should cause more people to substitute virtual travel for physical travel.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] Matthew Simmons explicitly calls for "liberating the workforce" by changing the corporate mindset from paying people to show up physically to work every day, to paying them instead for the work they do, from any location.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] This would allow more information workers to work from home either part-time or full-time, or from satellite offices or Internet cafes near to where they live, freeing them from long daily commutes to central offices.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] However, even full adoption of remote work by all eligible workers might only decrease energy consumption by about 1% (with present energy savings estimated at 0.01–0.04%).
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] By comparison, a 20% increase in automobile fuel economy would save 5.4%.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] The price rises of mid-2008 led to a variety of proposals to change the rules governing energy markets and energy futures markets, in order to prevent rises due to market speculation.
[src:jet-fuel/2000s-energy-crisis] On 26 July 2008, the United States House of Representatives passed the Energy Markets Emergency Act of 2008 (H.R.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The **Airbus A310** is a wide-body airliner designed and manufactured by Airbus Industrie GIE, then a consortium of European aerospace manufacturers.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Airbus had identified a demand for an aircraft smaller than the A300, the first twin-jet wide-body.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] On 7 July 1978, the A310 (initially the A300B10) was launched with orders from Swissair and Lufthansa.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] On 3 April 1982, the first prototype conducted its maiden flight, and the A310 received its type certificate on 11 March 1983.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Keeping the same eight-abreast cross-section, the A310 is 6.95 m (22 ft 10 in) shorter than the initial A300 variants, has a smaller wing, down from 260 to 219 m2 (2,800 to 2,360 sq ft), and a longer flying range up to 5,150 nautical miles (9,540 km; 5,930 mi).
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 introduced a two-crew glass cockpit, later adopted for the A300-600 with a common type rating.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] It was powered by the same General Electric CF6-80 or Pratt & Whitney JT9D then PW4000 turbofan jet engines.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] It can seat 220 passengers in two classes, or 240 in all-economy.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] It has overwing exits between the two main front and rear door pairs.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] In April 1983, the aircraft entered revenue service with Swissair, and competed with the Boeing 767-200, introduced six months before.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Its longer range and ETOPS certification allowed it to be operated on transatlantic flights.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] It was also available as a cargo aircraft and in military variants: the A310 MRT (multi-role transport), which was further developed into the A310 MRTT (multi-role tanker transport).
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The aircraft was replaced by the larger Airbus A330-200.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Production ended after 255 aircraft were produced, with the final A310 being delivered in June 1998.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] On 26 September 1967, the governments of France, West Germany and the United Kingdom signed a memorandum of understanding to commence the joint development of the 300-seat Airbus A300.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The French and West Germans reached a firm agreement on 29 May 1969, after the British withdrew from the project on 10 April 1969.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] This collaborative effort between the two states resulted in the production of the consortium's first airliner, known as the *Airbus A300*.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A300 was a wide-body medium-to-long range passenger airliner; it holds the distinction of being the first twin-engine wide-body aircraft in the world.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A300 would be produced in a range of models, and sold relatively well to airlines across the world, eventually reaching a total of 561 delivered aircraft during its production life.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] During the development of the earlier A300, a range of different aircraft size and capacity were studied by the consortium; the resulting Airbus A300B proposal was one of the smaller options.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] When the A300B1 prototypes emerged, a number of airlines issued requests for an aircraft with greater capacity, which resulted in the initial production A300B2 version.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] At the same time, there was great pressure for Airbus to validate itself beyond the design and manufacture of a single airliner.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] In response to these desires, Airbus explored the options for producing a smaller derivative of the A300B2.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] In order to minimise the associated research and development costs for the tentative project, Airbus chose to examine several early design studies performed during the A300 programme.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The company ultimately chose to prioritise its focus on one option, which became known as the *A300B10MC* (standing for *M*inimum *C*hange).
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] As envisioned, the airliner's capacity was reduced to a maximum of 220 passengers, which was viewed at the time as being a desired capacity amongst many airlines.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Another problem for the programme was presented in the form of inflation, the rate of which in the United Kingdom (one of the early members of the Airbus consortium) was around 35 per cent during 1979–80.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] This factor was responsible for significantly raising the program's development costs and, as a knock-on effect, increase the per-unit cost of the resulting airliner.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] During the development of the A300, British manufacturer Hawker Siddeley Aviation (HSA) had been appointed as the subcontractor to perform the manufacturing of the wing of the aircraft; shortly afterwards, the British government chose to withdraw from the newly formed venture during 1969.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] In 1977, HSA subsequently merged with three other British aircraft companies, resulting in the formation of British Aerospace (BAe).
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] By this point in time, the British government had publicly indicated its intentions to rejoin the Airbus programme.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] In May 1976, the French government entered into a series of discussions on cooperation, during which its representatives stated that the placing of an order by British Airways (BA) was a condition for the re-admission of the United Kingdom into Airbus Industrie as a full partner.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] However, both BA and Rolls-Royce had not relinquished their will to collaborate with the Americans in future aircraft endeavours and, in BA's case, procure American aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] At the 1978 Farnborough Air Show, Eric Varley, the British Secretary of State for Industry, announced that BAe was to rejoin Airbus Industrie and participate as a full partner from 1 January 1979 onwards.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Under the negotiated arrangement, BAe would be allocated a 20 per cent shareholding in Airbus Industrie, and would perform "a full part in the development and manufacturing of the A310".
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] From late 1977, prior to the Varley announcement, BAe had already commenced work on the design of the new wing at its facility in Hatfield.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] However, due to negotiations with Britain on its return to the Airbus consortium being protracted, alternative options were explored, including potentially manufacturing the wing elsewhere.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] At the same time as the British efforts, French aerospace firm Aérospatiale, German aircraft manufacturer Messerschmitt-Bölkow-Blohm (MBB), and Dutch-German joint venture company VFW-Fokker were also conducting their individual studies into possible options for the wing of the prospective airliner.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] At the April 1978 Hannover Air Show, Airbus exhibited a model of the proposed A310.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Its wing area, at 219.25 m2 (2,360.0 sq ft) was slightly larger than that studied, at 209 m2 (2,250 sq ft); its passenger cabin was twelve frames shorter than the A300, accommodating typical passenger loads of 195 in two-class, or 245 in all-economy.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] However, during the next twelve months, almost every aspect was further refined.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] On 9 June 1978, Swissair and Lufthansa developed a joint specification for the aircraft, and within a month, announced that they would place the launch orders.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] On 15 March, Swissair became the first airline to place a firm order for the type, announcing that it would acquire ten aircraft, with a further ten under option, to replace its McDonnell Douglas DC-9s on its major intra-European routes.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Lufthansa was quick to place a $240 million ten-aircraft order; additional orders from French operator Air France and Spanish airline Iberia shortly followed.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Increasingly strong interest in the tentative airliner, coupled with the recovery of the industry during the late 1970s, contributed to Airbus deciding to put the A310 into production on 7 July 1978.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] During the latter half of 1978, an order for ten A300s was placed by independent British airline Laker Airways, satisfying Airbus's demand for the placing of a British order for their aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] On 1 April 1979, Lufthansa decided to raise its commitment for the type to 25 aircraft, along with 25 options.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Two days later, Dutch operator KLM signed its order for ten aircraft and ten options at £238 million.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] On 6 July 1979, Air France announced that it had raised its order from four to thirty-five airliners.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Other airlines announcing orders for the A310 during 1979 included Martinair, Sabena, and Air Afrique.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Initially, a pair of distinct versions of the A310 had been planned by Airbus; the regional A310-100, and the transcontinental A310-200.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310-100 featured a range of 2,000 nmi (3,700 km; 2,300 mi) with 200 passengers, whilst the A310-200 possessed a higher MTOW and centre section fuel, being able to carry the same load a further 1,000 nmi (1,900 km; 1,200 mi).
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Basic engines offered for the type included the General Electric CF6-45B2 and Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7R4.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] At one point, British engine manufacturer Rolls-Royce was openly considering offering an engine for the A310, the Rolls-Royce RB.207, however, it ultimately chose to discard such efforts in favour of a smaller three-spool design, the RB.211.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The range of the A310 exceeds that of the A300 series, with the exception of the A300-600R, which in turn surpasses that of the A310-200.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The greater range of the A310 contributed to the airliner being used extensively by operators on transatlantic routes.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A300 and A310 introduced the concept of commonality: A300-600 and A310 pilots can cross-qualify for the other aircraft with one day of training.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Sales of the A310 continued through the early 1980s.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] On 3 April 1982, the prototype A310-200 airliner conducted its maiden flight; by this point, the type had accumulated a combined orders and options for 181 aircraft, which had been placed by fifteen airlines worldwide, which was a better start than the original A300.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The launch customer of A310, Swissair, became the launch operator in April 1983.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Over time, it had become clear that the longer-range series −200 aircraft was the more popular of the two models on offer.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] During 1979, in response to the lack of demand for the A310-100, Airbus decided to stop offering the lower gross weight model which had been originally proposed for Lufthansa; as a consequence, none of this variant were ultimately manufactured.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] During the early 1990s, demand for the aircraft began to slacken; there were no new A310 passenger orders placed during the late 1990s, in part due to the introduction of the newer and more advanced Airbus A330 during this time.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] As a result, on June 15, 1998, the last delivery of an A310 (msn.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] 706, reg.UK-31003) was made to Uzbekistan Airways.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310, along with its A300 stablemate, ceased production during July 2007, though an order from Iraqi Airways for five A310s had remained on the books until July 2008.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The remaining freighter sales were to be instead fulfilled by the new A330-200F derivative.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 had been commonly marketed as an introduction to wide-body operations for airlines based in developing countries.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The airliner was replaced in Airbus's range by the highly successful A330-200, which shares its fuselage cross-section.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Between 1983, and the last aircraft produced in 1998, 255 A310s were delivered.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A300 and A310 established Airbus as a competitor to Boeing, and allowed it to go ahead with the more ambitious A320, and A330 / A340 families.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The Royal Canadian Air Force (RCAF) currently operates a fleet of five Airbus CC-150 Polaris, civilian Airbus A310-300s, originally owned by Wardair, and subsequently Canadian Airlines International, after the airlines merged.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The aircraft were then sold to the Government of Canada, and converted for use as the primary long-distance transport aircraft as part of the RCAF's fleet of Royal Canadian Air Force VIP aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] As of January 2025, only 33 remain in service, with 22 being ACJs, eight being in passenger service (with Ariana Afghan Airlines (3), Iran Air (1), Iran Airtour (4) being the only remaining passenger operators) and three in cargo service with UPS Airlines.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The Airbus A310 is a medium- to long-range twin-engined wide-body jet airliner.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Initially a derivative of the A300, the aircraft had originally been designated the *A300B10*.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] It was essentially a shortened variant of the earlier aircraft; however, there were considerable differences between the two aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Specifically, the fuselage possessed the same cross-section, but being shorter than the A300, it provided capacity for a typical maximum of 200 passengers.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The rear fuselage was heavily re-designed, featuring altered tapering, while involved a move aft of the rear bulkhead to create additional capacity; this same design change was later transferred back to later variants of the A300, such as the A300-600 and A330/A340 fuselages.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 also had a different emergency exit configuration, consisting of four main doors (two at the front and two at the rear of the aircraft), and two smaller doors over the wings.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The wing of the A310 was redesigned, possessing a reduced span and wing area, and incorporating simpler single-slotted Fowler flaps designed by British Aerospace shortly following its decision to join the Airbus consortium.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Other changes to the wing included the elimination of the outer ailerons, which were occasionally referred to by the manufacturer as being "low speed ailerons", and the addition of electrically actuated spoilers.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The wing also featured common pylons, which were able to support all types of engines that were offered to customers to power the airliner.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] From 1985 onwards, the A310-300 introduced wingtip fences which reduced vortex drag and thus improved cruise fuel consumption by over 1.5%.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] A limited number of alterations were also performed to the airliner's tail unit, such as the adoption of smaller horizontal tail surfaces.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 was furnished with a two-crew glass cockpit configuration as standard, removing the requirement for a flight engineer; Airbus referred to this concept as the *Forward-Facing Crew Cockpit*.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The company had developed the cockpit to significantly enhance the aircraft's man-machine interface, thereby improving operational safety.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The same flight deck was incorporated into the A300-600, a move which increased commonality between the two types, and enabled a dual type rating to be achieved, this same approach was later used on many future Airbus aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] In addition to the two flying crew, provisions for third and fourth crew seats were present within the flight deck.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 was initially proposed with a choice of three engines: the General Electric CF6-80A1, the Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7R4D1, and the Rolls-Royce RB211-524.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 was launched with the Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7R4D1 or the General Electric CF6-80A3.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 was equipped with a modified undercarriage, derived from the A300; the landing gear were outfitted with carbon brakes, which were fitted as standard.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The structure of the airliner featured a high level of composite materials throughout both primary and secondary structures, increased beyond that of the earlier A300.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 is outfitted with integrated drive electrical generators along with auxiliary power unit, which were improved versions of those used on the A300.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 is available in two basic versions: the medium-range A310-200 and the longer-range A310-300.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The first version of the aircraft to be developed was the -200, but this was later joined by the -300, which then became the standard production version of the aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The short-range -100 variant was never developed due to low demand.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The first A310, the 162nd Airbus off the production line, made its maiden flight on 3 April 1982 powered by the earlier Pratt & Whitney JT9D-7R4D1 engines.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The -200 entered service with Swissair and Lufthansa a year later.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Late series -200 also featured wing fences identical to those of the -300.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The first three A310s were initially fitted with outboard ailerons; they were later removed once testing showed them to be unnecessary.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] A convertible version, the seats can be removed and cargo placed on the main deck, the A310-200C entered service with Martinair on 29 November 1984.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The freight version of the A310-200 was available as a new build, or as a conversion of existing wide-bodied aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] No production freighters of the A310-200F were produced.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The converted Airbus A310-200F entered service with FedEx Express in 1994.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] First flown on 8 July 1985, the -300 is dimensionally identical to the -200, although it provides an increased Maximum Take-Off Weight (MTOW) and an increase in range, provided by additional centre and horizontal stabiliser (trim-tank) fuel tanks.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] This model also introduced wingtip fences to improve aerodynamic efficiency, a feature that has since been retrofitted to some -200s.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The aircraft entered service in 1986 with Swissair.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310-300 incorporates a computerised fuel distribution system which allows it to be trimmed in flight, optimising the centre of gravity by shuttling up to 5,000 kg (11,000 lb) of fuel in and out of the horizontal stabiliser tank, controlled by the Centre of Gravity Control Computer.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] It can be easily converted for passenger or cargo transport: the seats can be removed and cargo placed on the main deck.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Operators such as FedEx Express acquired modified ex-passenger A310s, usually starting with the -300 version.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] No production freighters of the A310-300F were produced.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] The A310 has been operated by several air forces as a pure transport, the A310-300 MRT (Multi-Role Transport).
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] However several have now been converted to the A310 MRTT (Multi-Role Tanker Transport) configuration by EADS, providing an air-to-air refuelling capability.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] At least six have been completed; four by the German Air Force (Luftwaffe), and two by the Royal Canadian Air Force (RCAF).
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Three were converted at EADS EFW in Dresden, Germany; the other three at Lufthansa Technik in Hamburg, Germany.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] One A310 airframe became a scientific research laboratory dedicated to weightlessness.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] This reduced-gravity aircraft is used to realise parabolas, allowing to perform twenty-two seconds of weightlessness.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Operated by Novespace, subsidiary of CNES, French Space Agency, A310 Zero G is based at Bordeaux Mérignac airport.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] It also performs scientific flights, recreational flights under the Air Zero G brand, and movie special effects, such as for *The Mummy* (2017).
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] Below is a list of major differences between the A310 variants.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] As of April 2025, there are 48 A310 family aircraft in service.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] By the end of production, a total of 255 A310s had been ordered and delivered.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] As of September 2015 there have been 12 hull-loss accidents involving A310s with a total of 825 fatalities; and 9 hijackings with a total of five fatalities.
[src:jet-fuel/a310-300] According to the bar graph on Boeing's Statistical Summary of Commercial Jet Airplane Accidents, the A310 has the highest fatal hull loss rate and second highest total hull loss rate of any widebody commercial airliner, behind the MD-11.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:jet-fuel/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The discovery of adamantane in petroleum in 1933 launched a new field of chemistry dedicated to the synthesis and properties of polyhedral organic compounds.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane derivatives have found practical application as drugs, polymeric materials, and thermally stable lubricants.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Decker suggested the existence of adamantane, which he called **decaterpene**.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The first attempted laboratory synthesis was made in 1924 by German chemist Hans Meerwein using the reaction of formaldehyde with diethyl malonate in the presence of piperidine.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] This compound, later named Meerwein's ester, was used in the synthesis of adamantane and its derivatives.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Böttger tried to obtain adamantane using Meerwein's ester as precursor.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The product was not adamantane, but a derivative with a tricyclo[3.3.1.13,7] ring system.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Other researchers attempted to synthesize adamantane using phloroglucinol and derivatives of cyclohexanone, but also failed.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane was first synthesized by Vladimir Prelog in 1941 from Meerwein's ester.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] With a yield of 0.16%, the five-stage process (simplified in the image below) was impractical for commerce.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The method is still used to synthesize certain adamantane derivatives.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] This method increased the yield to 30–40% and provided an affordable source of adamantane; it therefore stimulated characterization of adamantane and is still used in laboratory practice.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The process is astonishingly robust: virtually any C10H16 alkane feedstock rearranges to adamantane in a strong Lewis acid.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The adamantane synthesis yield was later increased to 60% and 98% by ultrasound and superacid catalysis.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Today, adamantane is an affordable chemical compound with a cost of about two USD per gram.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] All the above methods yield adamantane as a polycrystalline powder.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Using this powder, single crystals can be grown from the melt, solution, or vapor phase (e.g. with the Bridgman–Stockbarger technique).
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Melt growth results in the worst crystalline quality with a mosaic spread in the X-ray reflection of about 1°.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The best crystals are obtained from the liquid phase, but the growth is impracticably slow – several months for a 5–10 mm crystal.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Growth from the vapor phase is a reasonable compromise in terms of speed and quality.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane is sublimed in a quartz tube placed in a furnace, which is equipped with several heaters maintaining a certain temperature gradient (about 10 °C/cm for adamantane) along the tube.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Crystallization starts at one end of the tube, which is kept near the freezing point of adamantane.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Slow cooling of the tube, while maintaining the temperature gradient, gradually shifts the melting zone (rate ~2 mm/hour), producing a single-crystal boule.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane was first isolated from petroleum by the Czech chemists S.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] They used fractional distillation of petroleum.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] They could produce only a few milligrams of adamantane, but noticed its high boiling and melting points.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Because of the (assumed) similarity of its structure to that of diamond, the new compound was named adamantane.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Petroleum remains a source of adamantane; the content varies from between 0.0001% and 0.03% depending on the oil field and is too low for commercial production.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Petroleum contains more than thirty derivatives of adamantane.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Their isolation from a complex mixture of hydrocarbons is possible due to their high melting point and the ability to distill with water vapor and form stable adducts with thiourea.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Pure adamantane is a colorless, crystalline solid with a characteristic camphor smell.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] It is practically insoluble in water, but readily soluble in nonpolar organic solvents.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane has an unusually high melting point for a hydrocarbon.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] At 270 °C, its melting point is much higher than other hydrocarbons with the same molecular weight, such as camphene (45 °C), limonene (−74 °C), ocimene (50 °C), terpinene (60 °C) or twistane (164 °C), or than a linear C10H22 hydrocarbon decane (−28 °C).
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] However, adamantane slowly sublimes even at room temperature.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane can be distilled with water vapor.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] As deduced by electron diffraction and X-ray crystallography, the molecule has Td symmetry.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The carbon–carbon bond lengths are 1.54 Å, almost identical to that of diamond.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The carbon–hydrogen distances are 1.112 Å.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] At ambient conditions, adamantane crystallizes in a face-centered cubic structure (space group Fm3m, *a* = 9.426 ± 0.008 Å, four molecules in the unit cell) containing orientationally disordered adamantane molecules.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] This structure transforms into an ordered, primitive, tetragonal phase (*a* = 6.641 Å, *c* = 8.875 Å) with two molecules per cell, either upon cooling to 208 K or pressurizing to above 0.5 GPa.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] This phase transition is of the first order; it is accompanied by an anomaly in the heat capacity, elastic, and other properties.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] In particular, whereas adamantane molecules freely rotate in the cubic phase, they are frozen in the tetragonal one; the density increases stepwise from 1.08 to 1.18 g/cm3, and the entropy changes by a significant amount of 1594 J/(mol·K).
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Elastic constants of adamantane were measured using large (centimeter-sized) single crystals and the ultrasonic echo technique.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The principal value of the elasticity tensor, C11, was deduced as 7.52, 8.20, and 6.17 GPa for the <110>, <111>, and <100> crystalline directions.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] For comparison, the corresponding values for crystalline diamond are 1161, 1174, and 1123 GPa.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The arrangement of carbon atoms is the same in adamantane and diamond; however, in the adamantane solid, molecules do not form a covalent lattice as in diamond, but interact through weak van der Waals forces.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] As a result, adamantane crystals are very soft and plastic.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectrum of adamantane consists of two poorly resolved signals, which correspond to sites 1 and 2 (see picture below).
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The 1H and 13C NMR chemical shifts are respectively 1.873 and 1.756 ppm and are 28.46 and 37.85 ppm.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The simplicity of these spectra is consistent with high molecular symmetry.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Mass spectra of adamantane and its derivatives are rather characteristic.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The main peak at *m*/*z* = 136 corresponds to the C 10H+ 16 ion.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Its fragmentation results in weaker signals as *m*/*z* = 93, 80, 79, 67, 41 and 39.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The infrared absorption spectrum of adamantane is relatively simple because of the high symmetry of the molecule.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane derivatives with different substituents at every nodal carbon sites are chiral.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Such optical activity was described in adamantane in 1969 with the four different substituents being hydrogen, bromine, methyl, and carboxyl.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The values of specific rotation are small and are usually within 1°.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Using the rules of systematic nomenclature, adamantane is called tricyclo[3.3.1.13,7]decane.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] However, IUPAC recommends using the name "adamantane".
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The adamantane molecule is composed of only carbon and hydrogen and has Td symmetry.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Therefore, its 16 hydrogen and 10 carbon atoms can be described by only two sites, which are labeled in the figure as **1** (4 equivalent sites) and **2** (6 equivalent sites).
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Structural relatives of adamantane are noradamantane and homoadamantane, which respectively contain one less and one more CH2 link than the adamantane.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The functional group derived from adamantane is adamantyl, formally named as 1-adamantyl or 2-adamantyl depending on which site is connected to the parent molecule.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantyl groups are a bulky pendant group used to improve the thermal and mechanical properties of polymers.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The chemistry of adamantane is dominated by the stability of the tertiary adamantanium cation, C10H+ 15, itself isolable when treating 1‑fluoro­adamantane with SbF5.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Radical reactions of adamantane also occur preferentially at the bridgehead due to steric hindrance.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] For example, sulfoxidation gives exclusively 1-adamantanesulfonic acid.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantanium's stability eases SN,1 substitution for 1‑adamantane derivatives.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Thus 1‑bromo­adamantane hydrolyzes in acid to 1‑hydroxy­adamantane, and the latter fluorolyzes to 1‑fluoro­adamantane.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] With unsubstituted adamantane, strong Brønsted acids and other comparable electrophiles abstract a hydride equivalent from a bridgehead.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] For example, nitrosyl salts or an applied voltage oxidize adamantane to the cation intermediate.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Under most conditions, the resulting adamantanium cation then attacks nearby nucleophiles, for a net substitution.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane also reacts with less exotic reagents.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Various brominators, including molecular bromine, react via an ionic pathway, and similar reactions are possible with gaseous fluorine (but chlorination is likely a radical reaction).
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The reaction products depend on the conditions, especially the presence and type of catalysis.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Boiling adamantane with bromine results in a monosubstituted adamantane, 1-bromadamantane.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The rate of bromination is accelerated upon addition of Lewis acids and is unchanged by irradiation or addition of free radicals.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane undergoes Koch-Haaf carboxylation with formic acid to give 1-adamantanecarboxylic acid...
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] ...and a Scholl-type arylation with benzene and acidic clay.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Nitration of adamantane is a difficult reaction characterized by moderate yields.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Direct nitration occurs best in glacial acetic acid.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Even though the end product is unsubstituted at the bridgeheads, they are mechanistically involved.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] A bridgehead cation forms initially before undergoing intermolecular hydride transfer.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Cations formed at a bridging carbon appear to equilibrate with a protoadamantyl cation: a ring expansion/contraction exchanges the roles of a neighboring bridgehead and the cationic center.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Indeed, if an adamantane bridgehead carbon is substituted to stabilize a positive charge, then cation formation along the bridges causes a semipinacol rearrangement.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Such processes can be reversed to substitute at multiple bridging carbons at simultaneously.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The carbonyl group of adamantanone is less reactive than most cyclic carbonyls, since (by symmetry) any adduct suffers from axial strain.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Nevertheless, sufficiently reactive reagents (e.g. alkyllithiums instead of Grignard reagents) allow further functionalization at the bridging site.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] For example, adamantanone is the starting compound for 2-adamantanecarbonitrile and 2-methyl-adamantane.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane itself enjoys few applications since it is merely an unfunctionalized hydrocarbon.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] It is used in some dry etching masks and polymer formulations.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] In solid-state NMR spectroscopy, adamantane is a common standard for chemical shift referencing.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] In dye lasers, adamantane may be used to extend the life of the gain medium; it cannot be photoionized under atmosphere because its absorption bands lie in the vacuum-ultraviolet region of the spectrum.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Photoionization energies have been determined for adamantane as well as for several bigger diamondoids.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] All medical applications known so far involve not pure adamantane, but its derivatives.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The first adamantane derivative used as a drug was amantadine – first (1967) as an antiviral drug against various strains of influenza and then to treat Parkinson's disease.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Polymers of adamantane have been patented as antiviral agents against HIV.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Influenza virus strains have developed drug resistance to amantadine and rimantadine, which are not effective against prevalent strains as of 2016.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane was recently identified as a key structural subunit in several synthetic cannabinoid designer drugs, namely AB-001 and SDB-001.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane is an attractive candidate for propellant in Hall-effect thrusters because it ionizes easily, can be stored in solid form rather than a heavy pressure tank, and is relatively nontoxic.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Some alkyl derivatives of adamantane have been used as a working fluid in hydraulic systems.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane-based polymers might find application for coatings of touchscreens, and there are prospects for using adamantane and its homologues in nanotechnology.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] For example, the soft cage-like structure of adamantane solid allows incorporation of guest molecules, which can be released inside the human body upon breaking the matrix.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Adamantane could be used as molecular building blocks for self-assembly of molecular crystals.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Many molecules and ions adopt adamantane-like cage structures.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Those include phosphorus trioxide P4O6, arsenic trioxide As4O6, phosphorus pentoxide P4O10 = (PO)4O6, phosphorus pentasulfide P4S10 = (PS)4S6, and hexamethylenetetramine C6N4H12 = N4(CH2)6.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Particularly notorious is tetramethylenedisulfotetramine, often shortened to "tetramine", a rodenticide banned in most countries for extreme toxicity to humans.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The silicon analogue of adamantane, sila-adamantane, was synthesized in 2005.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Arsenicin A is a naturally occurring organoarsenic chemical isolated from the New Caledonian sea sponge *Echinochalina bargibanti* and is the first known heterocycle to contain multiple arsenic atoms.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Conjoining adamantane cages produces higher diamondoids, such as diamantane (C14H20 – two fused adamantane cages), triamantane (C18H24), tetramantane (C22H28), pentamantane (C26H32), hexamantane (C26H30), etc.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] Their synthesis is similar to that of adamantane and like adamantane, they can also be extracted from petroleum, though at even much smaller yields.
[src:jet-fuel/adamantane] The related dication of 1,3-didehydroadamantane also has elevated stability due to the phenomenon called "three-dimensional aromaticity" or homoaromaticity.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The **AGM-86 ALCM** is an American subsonic air-launched cruise missile (ALCM) built by Boeing and operated by the United States Air Force.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This missile was developed to increase the effectiveness and survivability of the Boeing B-52G and B-52H Stratofortress strategic bombers, allowing the aircraft to deliver its payload from a great distance.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The missile hampers an enemy force's ability to respond and conduct air defense.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The concept started as a long-range drone aircraft that would act as a decoy, distracting Soviet air defenses from the bombers.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] As new lightweight nuclear weapons emerged in the 1960s, the design was modified with the intent of attacking missile and radar sites at the end of its flight.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Further development extended its range so much that it emerged as a weapon allowing the B-52s to launch their attacks while still well outside Soviet airspace, saturating their defenses with hundreds of tiny, low-flying targets that were extremely difficult to see on radar.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Early tests of the missile took place between 1983-1993, during which time 23 cruise missiles were tested over northern Canada under the "Canada-U.S.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The goal of the program was to simulate the climate and terrain similar to that of the northern Soviet Union, and to allow the North American Aerospace Defence Command (NORAD) to develop an anti-cruise capability.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Entering service in 1982 as part of the renewed American arms buildup during the Late Cold War, the ALCM so improved the capabilities of the US bomber force that the Soviets developed new technologies to counter the weapon.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Among these were airborne early warning aircraft and new weapons like the MiG-31 and Tor missile system specifically to shoot down the AGM-86.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The Air Force responded with the development of the AGM-129 ACM, which included stealth capabilities.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The ending of the Cold War led to cutbacks in this program, and its expensive maintenance eventually resulted in it being abandoned in favor of life extensions to the original ALCM.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Examples of the AGM-86A and AGM-86B are on display at the Steven F.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Udvar-Hazy Center of the National Air and Space Museum, near Washington, D.C.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The ALCM traces its history to the ADM-20 Quail missile, which began development in February 1956.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Quail was the ultimate outcome of several similar programs to develop a small decoy aircraft that would be launched from bombers during their approach to targets, presenting false targets to saturate the defenses and allow the bombers to escape an attack.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The small jet-powered drone aircraft had a simple inertial navigation system (INS) that allowed it to fly a pre-programmed course that would make it visible to known Soviet defensive sites.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] A number of radar jammers and radar reflectors were intended to make it appear like a B-52 on a radar display.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Quail was designed in the mid-1950s when the normal attack profile for a strategic bomber was to fly as high and fast as possible to reduce the time the defenders had to respond to the aircraft before it flew out of range.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This was effective against interceptor aircraft but of little use against surface-to-air missiles (SAMs), whose attack times were measured in seconds.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This led to the adoption of low-level attacks, where the bombers would fly below the radar horizon so they could not be seen on ground-based radars.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Quail, originally designed for the high-altitude mission, was modified with the addition of a barometric altimeter to allow it to fly at lower altitudes.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Doing so seriously limited its effective range and flight time.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In the early 1960s, the Air Force began to question the usefulness of Quail in the face of improving Soviet defenses.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Looking for another solution to the Soviet SAM problem, in 1964 the Air Force began developing a new system that would directly attack the missile sites rather than confuse them.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This emerged as the AGM-69 SRAM, with a range of about 50 nautical miles (93 km; 58 mi), allowing it to be launched from outside the roughly 20 nautical miles (37 km; 23 mi) range of the SA-2 Guideline missiles it faced.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Flying at Mach 3, it quickly flew out in front of the bombers, reaching the missile site before the bomber flew into the range of the SA-2.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] While highly capable against known missile locations, SRAM could do nothing to defend against unknown sites, nor help with the problem of interceptor aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] To deal with these threats, Quail continued to be carried, typically in pairs, providing some defense against these other threats.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In January 1968, a new requirement emerged for a modern version of Quail for this new mission, the Subsonic Cruise Aircraft Decoy, or SCAD.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] SCAD was designed specifically to fit onto the same rotary launcher used by SRAM, allowing a single aircraft to carry multiple SRAM and SCAD and launch either at any time.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This led to it being the same 14 foot (4.3 m) length as SRAM, and the use of a fuselage with a triangular cross-section, which maximized the usable volume on the rotary launchers.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The system was otherwise similar to Quail, using a simple inertial navigation system (INS) allowing the missile to fly a pre-programmed course.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Soon after development began, it was noted that the very small nuclear warheads being developed at that time could be fit to SCAD without seriously affecting its performance as a decoy.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This would allow it to act as a decoy for much of its flight, and then deliberately approach a selected defensive site and attack it.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] As such, the program was renamed Subsonic Cruise Armed Decoy, retaining the SCAD acronym.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] For this role, the accuracy of the original INS guidance hardware was not enough.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] While a similar system was also used in SRAM, its shorter range and much shorter flight times meant the drift rate of the system was not a serious concern as long as the bomber could feed it accurate information just before launch, to "zero out" the drift.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In contrast, SCAD was designed to fly over much longer ranges and slower speeds, resulting in longer flight times and increasing the problem with drift; even with the drift "zeroed out" just before launch, subsequent drift during the longer flight would accumulate to an unacceptable error.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] To provide the accuracy needed to attack the SAM sites with a small warhead, some system was needed to zero out the drift in-flight, and for this need, a radar-based TERCOM system was added.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Development was approved in July 1970, and it was given the designation ZAGM-86A, the Z indicating its initial development status.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] As SCAD moved from the pure-decoy role to decoy-and-attack, this meant it would be able to carry out the same mission as SRAM, but from much longer range.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Accordingly, in June 1973, SCAD was canceled in favor of a system dedicated purely to the long-range attack mission.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The original designation number remained, but the name changed to reflect the new mission, becoming the Air Launched Cruise Missile, or ALCM.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The first example, similar to the original SCAD in most ways, flew for the first time in March 1976, and its new guidance system was first tested that September.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In January 1977, the missile was ordered into full-scale production.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Compared to the models that entered service in the 1980s, the A-model had a distinctive look; the nose tapered sharply to a triangular point giving it a shark-like appearance, compared to the later models which had a more rounded conventional appearance.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Meanwhile, the Air Force had also issued a requirement for a version with a much longer 1,500 nautical miles (2,800 km; 1,700 mi) range.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This would allow the bombers to launch their missiles from far off the Russian coast, placing it outside the range of the interceptors as well.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] To reach the intended range, this new Extended Range Version (ERV) would have to be lengthened to contain more fuel, or external fuel tanks would have to be added.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Either change would make it too large to fit on the SRAM launchers and the extended-fuselage version would be too large to fit in the bomb bay of the new B-1 Lancer bomber.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The Air Force intended to replace the original ALCM with the new version at some future date.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The Navy was also in the midst of its own cruise missile project, the Sea-Launched Cruise Missile (SLCM), which ultimately emerged as the BGM-109 Tomahawk, which was similar to ALCM in many ways.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In 1977, the Air Force and Navy were ordered to collaborate under the "Joint Cruise Missile Project", JCMP, with the intention of using as many parts in common as possible.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] After considering the two designs, the Air Force agreed to modify the ALCM with the SLCM's McDonnell Douglas AN/DPW-23 TERCOM system, as well as using its Williams F107 turbofan engine.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] While the JCMP program was taking place, the B-1 was canceled.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This eliminated the need for ALCM to fit in the B-1's bomb bay, and the length limitations that implied.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The Air Force decided to cancel production of the A-model ALCM, and replace it with either an air-launched version of the SLCM, or the ERV.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The ERV flew in August 1979, and was declared the winner of the head-to-head fly-off against the SLCM in March 1980.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Production of the initial 225 AGM-86B missiles began in fiscal year 1980.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The AGM-86B reached operational status in December 1982, on the B-52G with the 416th Bombardment Wing / 668th Bombardment Squadron, Griffiss Air Force Base, New York.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Eventually, the missile was deployed across the entire B-52G and B-52H fleet throughout Strategic Air Command.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Integration and successful flight testing did occur with the B-1B (involving moving the bulkhead between the forward and intermediate stores bay forward one position) - however the AGM-86 was never operationally deployed on the B-1.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Production of a total 1,715 missiles was completed in October 1986.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] More than 100 launches have taken place since then, with a 90% approximate success rate.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In June 1986 a limited number of AGM-86B missiles were converted to carry a high-explosive blast/fragmentation warhead and an internal GPS.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] They were redesignated as the AGM-86C CALCM (Conventional Air-Launched Cruise Missile).
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This modification also replaced the B model's TERCOM and integrated a GPS capability with the existing inertial navigation system computer .
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In 1996 and 1997, 200 additional CALCMs were produced from excess ALCMs.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] These missiles, designated Block I, incorporate improvements such as a larger and improved conventional payload (1,360 kg, 3,000 lb blast class), a multi-channel GPS receiver and integration of the buffer box into the GPS receiver.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The upgraded avionics package was retrofitted into all existing CALCM (Block 0) so all AGM-86C missiles are electronically identical.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] All variants of the AGM-86 missile are powered by a Williams F107 turbofan jet engine that propels it at sustained subsonic speeds and can be launched from aircraft at both high and low altitudes.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The missile deploys its folded wings, tail surfaces and engine inlet after launch.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] AGM-86B/C/D missiles increase flexibility in target selection.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] AGM-86B missiles can be air-launched in large numbers by the bomber force.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] B-52H bombers carry six AGM-86B or AGM-86C missiles on each of two externally mounted pylons and eight internally on a rotary launcher, giving the B-52H a maximum capacity of 20 missiles per aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] An enemy force would have to counterattack each of the missiles individually, making defense against them costly and complicated.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The enemy's defenses are further hampered by the missiles' small size and low-altitude flight capability, which makes them difficult to detect on radar.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The nuclear armed AGM-86B uses a terrain contour-matching guidance system (TERCOM) to fly to its assigned target.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] It can carry a single W80 thermonuclear warhead, with a yield of 5 or 150 kilotons.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] A modified variant of the B61, it was mainly designed for use on ground and air-launched cruise missiles.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The AGM-86C/D CALCM carries a conventional high-explosive payload rather than a thermonuclear payload.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This is a fragmentation warhead in the AGM-86C and a unitary penetrating warhead in the AGM-86D.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The AGM-86C/D uses an onboard Global Positioning System (GPS) coupled with its inertial navigation system (INS) to navigate in flight.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This allows the missile to guide itself to the target with pinpoint accuracy.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Litton Guidance and Control, and Interstate Electronics Corporation (one of the companies acquired by L3Harris) were the guidance contractors for the C model.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The CALCM became operational in January 1991 at the onset of Operation Desert Storm.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Seven B-52Gs from Barksdale AFB launched 35 missiles at designated launch points in the U.S.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Central Command's area of responsibility to attack high-priority targets in Iraq.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] These "round-robin" missions marked the beginning of the operation's Air Force component and were the longest known aircraft combat sorties in history at the time (more than 14,000 miles (23,000 km) and 35 hours of flight).
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] CALCM's next employment occurred in September 1996 during Operation Desert Strike.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In response to Iraq's continued hostilities against the Kurds in northern Iraq, the Air Force launched 13 CALCMs in a joint attack with the Navy.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] This mission has put the CALCM program in the spotlight for future modifications.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Operation Desert Strike was also the combat debut of the B-52H and the carriage of the CALCM on the weapons bay-mounted Common Strategic Rotary Launcher (CSRL).
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] During the Operation Desert Storm, the CALCM had been carried on the B-52G and wing-mounted pylons.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The CALCM was also used in Operation Desert Fox in 1998, Operation Allied Force in 1999, and Operation Iraqi Freedom in 2003.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Operation Iraqi Freedom was also the combat debut of the AGM-86D, a further development of the missile which replaced the blast/fragmentation warhead of the AGM-86C with a penetrating warhead.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In 2007 the USAF announced its intention to retire all of its AGM-129 ACMs and to reduce the ALCM fleet by more than 500 missiles, leaving 528 nuclear cruise missiles.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The ALCM force will be consolidated at Minot Air Force Base, North Dakota, and all excess cruise missile bodies will be destroyed.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The reductions are a result of the Strategic Offensive Reductions Treaty requirement to go below 2,200 deployed nuclear weapons by 2012, with the AGM-129 ACM chosen for disposal because it has reliability problems and high maintenance costs.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Even with the SLEP (service life extension program), the remaining AGM-86s were to reach their end of service by 2020, leaving the B-52 without a nuclear mission.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] However, in 2012, the USAF announced plans to extend the useful life of the missiles until at least 2030.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] To replace the ALCM, the USAF planned to award a contract for the development of the new Long-Range Stand-Off (LRSO) weapon in 2015.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Unlike the AGM-86, the LRSO will be carried on multiple aircraft, including the B-52, the B-2 Spirit, and the Northrop Grumman B-21.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Like the AGM-86, the LRSO can be armed with either a conventional or nuclear warhead.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The LRSO program is to develop a weapon that can penetrate and survive integrated air defense systems and prosecute strategic targets.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Both conventional and nuclear versions of the weapon are required to reach initial operational capability (IOC) before the retirement of their respective ALCM versions, around 2030.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The technology development contracts were to be submitted before the end of 2012.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] In March 2014 a further three-year delay in the project was announced by the Department of Defense, delaying a contract award until fiscal year 2018.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The House Armed Services Committee moved to reject this delay.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The delay was caused by financial pressures and an uncertain acquisition plan, and allowed by the long remaining service life left for the AGM-86 and lack of urgent necessity compared to other defense needs.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] As of August 24, 2017, the Department of Defense has awarded both Lockheed Martin and Raytheon Corporations with $900 million ($1.18 billion in 2025) to develop the LRSO.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] Contracts end in 2022, when the Department of Defense will select one design to continue further developments.
[src:jet-fuel/agm-86-alcm] The CALCM was retired on 20 November 2019, replaced in the conventional standoff strike role by the AGM-158B JASSM-ER.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] In 1898, a group of scientists and engineers, led by chemist, industry leader, and proponent of standardization Charles Dudley, formed the American Society for Testing Material (ASTM) to address the frequent rail breaks affecting the fast-growing railroad industry.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] The group developed a standard for the steel used to fabricate rails.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] In 1961 the name "American Society for Testing and Materials" was adopted.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] In 2001, ASTM officially changed its name to "ASTM International" and added the tagline "Standards Worldwide".
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] In 2014, the tagline changed to "Helping our World Work better." ASTM International had offices in Belgium, Canada, China, Peru, Washington, D.C., and West Conshohocken, PA.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] In April 2016, the Safety Equipment Institute (SEI) became a subsidiary of ASTM International.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] SEI is an accredited third-party certification organization that certifies various types of personal protective equipment to industry consensus standards.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that the European Committee for Standardization (CEN) and ASTM International agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Membership in the organization is open to anyone interested in its activities.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Standards are developed within committees, and new committees are formed as needed, upon request of interested members.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Membership in most committees is voluntary and is initiated by the member's request, not by appointment or invitation.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Members are classified as users, producers, consumers, and "general interest".
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] The latter includes academics and consultants.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Users include industry users, who may be producers in the context of other technical commodities, and end-users such as consumers.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] To meet the requirements of antitrust laws, producers must constitute less than 50% of every committee or subcommittee, and votes are limited to one per producer company.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Because of these restrictions, there can be a substantial waiting-list of producers seeking organizational memberships on the more popular committees.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Members can participate without a formal vote and their input will be fully considered.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] As of 2015, ASTM has more than 30,000 members, including over 1,150 organizational members, from more than 140 countries.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] The members serve on one or more of 140+ ASTM Technical Committees.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] ASTM International has several awards for contributions to standards authorship, including the ASTM International Award of Merit (the organization's highest award) ASTM International is classified by the United States Internal Revenue Service as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] In 2018, ASTM International launched the Additive Manufacturing Center of Excellence (AM CoE), a global initiative uniting industry, government, and academia to accelerate research, development, standardization, certification, and industrialization of additive manufacturing (AM).
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Headquartered in Washington, D.C., with a network of experts across the Americas, Europe, and Asia, the AM CoE focuses on bridging the gap between cutting-edge research and consensus-based standards.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] These initiatives aim to close standardization gaps, support qualification frameworks, and promote the broader adoption of additive manufacturing technologies across the aerospace, defense industry, medical devices, automotive industry, and energy sectors.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] In 2021, ASTM International acquired Wohlers Associates, a consulting firm and market intelligence provider in additive manufacturing and 3D printing.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Wohlers Associates provides industry analysis and forecasts covering hardware, software, materials, and applications related to additive manufacturing.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Funded by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), the Standardization Center of Excellence (SCOE) is a more recent initiative under ASTM International.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] SCOE focuses on advancing innovation and standardization for critical and emerging technologies, offering a coordinated framework connecting R&D, standards development, workforce readiness, and regulatory alignment.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] The SCOE enables cross-industry collaboration to ensure that next-generation technologies are developed, validated, and deployed with trusted, globally harmonized standards.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] ASTM International has no role in requiring or enforcing compliance with its standards.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] The standards may become mandatory when referenced by an external contract, corporation, regulation, law, or government.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] In the United States, ASTM standards have been adopted by incorporation or reference in many federal, state, and municipal government regulations.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] The 1995 National Technology Transfer and Advancement Act requires the Federal government to use privately developed consensus standards whenever possible.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] The Act reflects what had long been recommended as best practice within the Federal government.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Other governments, including state and foreign, have also referenced ASTM standards.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] Corporations doing international business may choose to reference an ASTM standard.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] All toys sold in the United States must meet the safety requirements of ASTM F963, Standard Consumer Safety Specification for Toy Safety, as part of the Consumer Product Safety Improvement Act (CPSIA) of 2008.
[src:jet-fuel/astm-international] The law makes the ASTM F963 standard a mandatory requirement for toys while the Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) studies the standard's effectiveness and issues final consumer guidelines for toy safety.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet fuel is a mixture of a variety of hydrocarbons.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Because the exact composition of jet fuel varies widely based on petroleum source, it is impossible to define jet fuel as a ratio of specific hydrocarbons.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet fuel is therefore defined as a performance specification rather than a chemical compound.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Furthermore, the range of molecular mass between hydrocarbons (or different carbon numbers) is defined by the requirements for the product, such as the freezing point or smoke point.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Kerosene-type jet fuel (including Jet A and Jet A-1, JP-5, and JP-8) has a carbon number distribution between about 8 and 16 (carbon atoms per molecule); wide-cut or naphtha-type jet fuel (including Jet B and JP-4), between about 5 and 15.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Fuel for piston-engine powered aircraft (usually a high-octane gasoline known as avgas) has a high volatility to improve its carburetion characteristics and high autoignition temperature to prevent preignition in high compression aircraft engines.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Turbine engines (as with diesel engines) can operate with a wide range of fuels because fuel is injected into the hot combustion chamber.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet and gas turbine (turboprop, helicopter) aircraft engines typically use lower cost fuels with higher flash points, which are less flammable and therefore safer to transport and handle.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The first axial compressor jet engine in widespread production and combat service, the Junkers Jumo 004 used on the Messerschmitt Me 262A fighter and the Arado Ar 234B jet recon-bomber, burned either a special synthetic "J2" fuel or diesel fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Gasoline was a third option but unattractive due to high fuel consumption.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Other fuels used were kerosene or kerosene and gasoline mixtures.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Pressure to move from Jet fuel to **sustainable aviation fuel**, i.e.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Aviation biofuel or Electrofuel, has existed since before the 2016 Paris Agreement.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Most jet fuels in use since the end of World War II are kerosene-based.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Both British and American standards for jet fuels were first established at the end of World War II.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] British standards derived from standards for kerosene use for lamps—known as paraffin in the UK—whereas American standards derived from aviation gasoline practices.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Over the subsequent years, details of specifications were adjusted, such as minimum freezing point, to balance performance requirements and availability of fuels.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Very low temperature freezing points reduce the availability of fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Higher flash point products required for use on aircraft carriers are more expensive to produce.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] In the United States, ASTM International produces standards for civilian fuel types, and the U.S.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Department of Defense produces standards for military use.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The British Ministry of Defence establishes standards for both civil and military jet fuels.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] For reasons of inter-operational ability, British and United States military standards are harmonized to a degree.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] In Russia and the CIS members, grades of jet fuels are covered by the State Standard (GOST) number, or a Technical Condition number, with the principal grade available being TS-1.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Both Jet A and Jet A-1 have a flash point higher than 38 °C (100 °F), with an autoignition temperature of 210 °C (410 °F).
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet A-1 is also known as AVTUR (aviation turbine) fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Vehicles, pipelines, and storage tanks containing Jet A or Jet A-1 should be marked with black bands, and for vehicles and tanks should also be marked with "Jet A" or "Jet A-1" in white text on a black background.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The differences between Jet A and Jet A-1 are twofold.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The other difference is the mandatory addition of an antistatic additive to Jet A-1 fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet A fuel must reach ASTM specification D1655 (Jet A).
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet B is a naphtha-kerosene fuel that is used for its enhanced cold-weather performance.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] However, Jet B's lighter composition makes it more dangerous to handle.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] For this reason, it is rarely used, except in very cold climates.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] A blend of approximately 30% kerosene and 70% gasoline, it is known as wide-cut fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It has a very low freezing point of −60 °C (−76 °F), and a low flash point as well.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It is primarily used in northern Canada and Alaska, where the extreme cold makes its low freezing point necessary, and which helps mitigate the danger of its lower flash point.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet B is also known as AVTAG (aviation turbine gasoline).
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The GOST standard 10227 specifies civilian fuels, among which are TS-1, T-1, T-1S, T2 and RT.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Military fuels such as T-1pp, T-8V (aka T-8B) and T-6 are specified by GOST 12308.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Icing inhibitors are specified by GOST 8313.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Some researchers refer to T-6 as "ram rocket fuel"; others have patented a method used to produce T-1pp from a mixture of T-6 and RT, the latter of which has been characterized as "unified Russian fuel for sub- and supersonic aircraft".
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] TS-1 is a jet fuel made to Russian standard GOST 10227 for enhanced cold-weather performance.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It has somewhat higher volatility than Jet A-1 (flash point is 28 °C (82 °F) minimum).
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It has a very low freezing point, below −50 °C (−58 °F).
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] As the aviation industry's jet kerosene demands have increased to more than 5% of all refined products derived from crude, it has been necessary for the refiner to optimize the yield of jet kerosene, a high-value product, by varying process techniques.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] New processes have allowed flexibility in the choice of crudes, the use of coal tar sands as a source of molecules and the manufacture of synthetic blend stocks.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Due to the number and severity of the processes used, it is often necessary and sometimes mandatory to use additives.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] These additives may, for example, prevent the formation of harmful chemical species or improve a property of a fuel to prevent further engine wear.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It is very important that jet fuel be free from water contamination.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] During flight, the temperature of the fuel in the tanks decreases, due to the low temperatures in the upper atmosphere.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] This causes precipitation of the dissolved water from the fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The separated water then drops to the bottom of the tank because it is denser than the fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Since the water is no longer in solution, it can form droplets which can supercool to below 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] If these supercooled droplets collide with a surface they can freeze and may result in blocked fuel inlet pipes.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] This was the cause of the British Airways Flight 38 accident.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Removing all water from fuel is impractical; therefore, fuel heaters are usually used on commercial aircraft to prevent water in fuel from freezing.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] There are several methods for detecting water in jet fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] A visual check may detect high concentrations of suspended water, as this causes the fuel to become hazy in appearance.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] An industry standard chemical test for the detection of free water in jet fuel uses a water-sensitive filter pad that turns green if the fuel exceeds the specification limit of 30 ppm (parts per million) free water.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Military organizations around the world use a different classification system of JP (for "Jet Propellant") numbers.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Some are almost identical to their civilian counterparts and differ only by the amounts of a few additives; Jet A-1 is similar to JP-8, Jet B is similar to JP-4.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Other military fuels are highly specialized products and are developed for very specific applications.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] specified in 1944 by the United States government (AN-F-32).
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The low freezing point requirement limited availability of the fuel and it was soon superseded by other "wide cut" jet fuels which were kerosene-naphtha or kerosene-gasoline blends.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] an obsolete type developed during World War II.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] JP-2 was intended to be easier to produce than JP-1 since it had a higher freezing point, but was never widely used.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] was an attempt to improve availability of the fuel compared to JP-1 by widening the cut and loosening tolerances on impurities to ensure ready supply.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] r's pot still could convert at least half of any crude to jet fuel".
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It was even more volatile than JP-2 and had high evaporation loss in service.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] than JP-1, but was preferred because of its greater availability.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] (aviation turbine gasoline/fuel systems icing inhibitor) fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] , where the risk from fire is particularly great.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] , Marine Corps air stations and Coast Guard air stations host both sea and land based naval aircraft, these installations will also typically fuel their shore-based aircraft with JP-5, thus precluding the need to maintain separate fuel facilities for JP-5 and non-JP-5 fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Similarly, China named their navy fuel RP-5.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] , and it does not contain antistatic agents.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] These fuels require unique additives that are necessary for military aircraft and engine fuel systems.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It was similar to JP-5 but with a lower freezing point and improved thermal oxidative stability.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] When the XB-70 program was cancelled, the JP-6 specification, MIL-J-25656, was also cancelled.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] required to prevent boiloff caused by aerodynamic heating.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] medium for aircraft air conditioning and hydraulic systems and engine accessories.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It is specified by MIL-DTL-83133 and British Defence Standard 91-87.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The United States military uses JP-8 as a "universal fuel" in both turbine-powered aircraft and diesel-powered ground vehicles.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It was first introduced at NATO bases in 1978.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It is also known as AVTUR/FSII (aviation turbine/fuel systems icing inhibitor) fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] (tetrahydrodimethyldicyclopentadiene) produced by catalytic hydrogenation of methylpentadiene dimer.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It is also used by the Tomahawk jet-powered subsonic cruise missile.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] and an additive to improve thermal oxidative stability officially known as "Thermally Stable Jet Fuel".
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] designates a series of experimental boron-containing "high energy fuels" intended for long range aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The toxicity and undesirable residues of the fuel made it difficult to use.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] removed the principal application of zip fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet fuel is very similar to diesel fuel, and in some cases, may be used in diesel engines.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] As a result, only a few aircraft engine manufacturers, most notably Thielert and Austro Engine, have begun offering aircraft diesel engines which run on jet fuel, which may simplify airport logistics by reducing the number of fuel types required.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet fuel is available in most places in the world, whereas avgas is only widely available in a few countries which have a large number of general aviation aircraft.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] A diesel engine may be more fuel-efficient than an avgas engine.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] However, very few diesel aircraft engines have been certified by aviation authorities.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Diesel aircraft engines are uncommon today, even though opposed-piston aviation diesel powerplants such as the Junkers Jumo 205 family had been used during the Second World War.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet fuel is often used in diesel-powered ground-support vehicles at airports.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] However, jet fuel tends to have poor lubricating ability in comparison to diesel, which increases wear in fuel injection equipment.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] An additive may be required to restore its lubricity.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet fuel is more expensive than diesel fuel but the logistical advantages of using one fuel can offset the extra expense of its use in certain circumstances.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Jet fuel contains more sulfur, up to 1,000 ppm, which therefore means it has better lubricity and does not currently require a lubricity additive as all pipeline diesel fuels require.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The introduction of Ultra Low Sulfur Diesel or ULSD brought with it the need for lubricity modifiers.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Pipeline diesels before ULSD were able to contain up to 500 ppm of sulfur and were called Low Sulfur Diesel or LSD.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] In the United States LSD is now only available to the off-road construction, locomotive and marine markets.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] As more EPA regulations are introduced, more refineries are hydrotreating their jet fuel production, thus limiting the lubricating abilities of jet fuel, as determined by ASTM Standard D445.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] JP-8, which is similar to Jet A-1, is used in NATO diesel vehicles as part of the single-fuel policy.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Fischer–Tropsch (FT) Synthesized Paraffinic Kerosene (SPK) synthetic fuels are certified for use in United States and international aviation fleets at up to 50% in a blend with conventional jet fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Both FT and HEFA based SPKs blended with JP-8 are specified in MIL-DTL-83133H.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Some synthetic jet fuels show a reduction in pollutants such as SOx, NOx, particulate matter, and sometimes carbon emissions.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It is envisaged that usage of synthetic jet fuels will increase air quality around airports which will be particularly advantageous at inner city airports.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Qatar Airways became the first airline to operate a commercial flight on a 50:50 blend of synthetic Gas to Liquid (GTL) jet fuel and conventional jet fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The natural gas derived synthetic kerosene for the six-hour flight from London to Doha came from Shell's GTL plant in Bintulu, Malaysia.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The world's first passenger aircraft flight to use only synthetic jet fuel was from Lanseria International Airport to Cape Town International Airport on September 22, 2010.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Chemist Heather Willauer is leading a team of researchers at the U.S.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Naval Research Laboratory who are developing a process to make jet fuel from seawater.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The technology requires an input of electrical energy to separate Oxygen (O2) and Hydrogen (H2) gas from seawater using an iron-based catalyst, followed by an oligomerization step wherein carbon monoxide (CO) and hydrogen are recombined into long-chain hydrocarbons, using zeolite as the catalyst.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The technology is expected to be deployed in the 2020s by U.S.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Navy warships, especially nuclear-powered aircraft carriers.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] On February 8, 2021, the world's first scheduled passenger flight flew with some synthetic kerosene from a non-fossil fuel source.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] 500 liters of synthetic kerosene was mixed with regular jet fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Synthetic kerosene was produced by Shell and the flight was operated by KLM.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] On August 8, 2007, Air Force Secretary Michael Wynne certified the B-52H as fully approved to use the FT blend, marking the formal conclusion of the test program.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] This program is part of the Department of Defense Assured Fuel Initiative, an effort to develop secure domestic sources for the military energy needs.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The Pentagon hopes to reduce its use of crude oil from foreign producers and obtain about half of its aviation fuel from alternative sources by 2016.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] With the B-52 now approved to use the FT blend, the USAF will use the test protocols developed during the program to certify the Boeing C-17 Globemaster III and then the Rockwell B-1B Lancer to use the fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] To test these two aircraft, the USAF has ordered 281,000 US gal (1,060,000 L) of FT fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The USAF intends to test and certify every airframe in its inventory to use the fuel by 2011.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] They will also supply over 9,000 US gal (34,000 L; 7,500 imp gal) to NASA for testing in various aircraft and engines.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The USAF has certified the B-1B, B-52H, C-17, Lockheed Martin C-130J Super Hercules, McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom (as QF-4 target drones), McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle, Lockheed Martin F-22 Raptor, and Northrop T-38 Talon to use the synthetic fuel blend.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Air Force's C-17 Globemaster III, F-16 and F-15 are certified for use of hydrotreated renewable jet fuels.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The USAF plans to certify over 40 models for fuels derived from waste oils and plants by 2013.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Army is considered one of the few customers of biofuels large enough to potentially bring biofuels up to the volume production needed to reduce costs.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Navy has also flown a Boeing F/A-18E/F Super Hornet dubbed the "Green Hornet" at 1.7 times the speed of sound using a biofuel blend.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) funded a $6.7 million project with Honeywell UOP to develop technologies to create jet fuels from biofeedstocks for use by the United States and NATO militaries.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] In April 2011, four USAF F-15E Strike Eagles flew over the Philadelphia Phillies opening ceremony using a blend of traditional jet fuel and synthetic biofuels.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] This flyover made history as it was the first flyover to use biofuels in the Department of Defense.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The air transport industry is responsible for 2–3 percent of man-made carbon dioxide emitted.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Boeing estimates that biofuels could reduce flight-related greenhouse-gas emissions by 60 to 80 percent.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Solazyme produced the world's first 100 percent algae-derived jet fuel, Solajet, for both commercial and military applications.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Oil prices increased about fivefold from 2003 to 2008, raising fears that world petroleum production is becoming unable to keep up with demand.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The fact that there are few alternatives to petroleum for aviation fuel adds urgency to the search for alternatives.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Twenty-five airlines were bankrupted or stopped operations in the first six months of 2008, largely due to fuel costs.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] In 2015 ASTM approved a modification to Specification D1655 Standard Specification for Aviation Turbine Fuels to permit up to 50 ppm (50 mg/kg) of FAME (fatty acid methyl ester) in jet fuel to allow higher cross-contamination from biofuel production.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Worldwide demand of jet fuel has been steadily increasing since 1980.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Around 30% of the worldwide consumption of jet fuel is in the US (1,398,130 barrels/day in 2012).
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] It is sometimes suggested that the Chicago Convention precludes the taxation of aviation fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The Chicago Convention does not preclude a fuel tax on domestic flights or on refuelling before international flights.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Article 15 of the Chicago Convention is also sometimes said to ban fuel taxes.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] In the European Union, commercial aviation fuel is exempt from taxation, according to the 2003 Energy Taxation Directive.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] EU member states may tax jet fuel via bilateral agreements, however no such agreements exist.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] In the United States, most states tax jet fuel.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] General health hazards associated with exposure to jet fuel vary according to its components, exposure duration (acute vs. long-term), route of administration (dermal vs. respiratory vs. oral), and exposure phase (vapor vs. aerosol vs. raw fuel).
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Kerosene-based hydrocarbon fuels are complex mixtures which may contain up to 260+ aliphatic and aromatic hydrocarbon compounds including toxicants such as benzene, n-hexane, toluene, xylenes, trimethylpentane, methoxyethanol, naphthalenes.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] While time-weighted average hydrocarbon fuel exposures can often be below recommended exposure limits, peak exposure can occur, and the health impact of occupational exposures is not fully understood.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] Evidence of the health effects of jet fuels comes from reports on both temporary or persisting biological from acute, subchronic, or chronic exposure of humans or animals to kerosene-based hydrocarbon fuels, or the constituent chemicals of these fuels, or to fuel combustion products.
[src:jet-fuel/jet-fuel] The effects studied include: cancer, skin conditions, respiratory disorders, immune and hematological disorders, neurological effects, visual and hearing disorders, renal and hepatic diseases, cardiovascular conditions, gastrointestinal disorders, genotoxic and metabolic effects.
